WEBVTT

00:01.000 --> 00:08.583
♪

00:08.583 --> 00:09.500
HEATHER:
Up straight. Up straight.

00:09.500 --> 00:10.875
It’s like there’s
a string on your head.

00:10.875 --> 00:12.000
It’s just pulling you forward.

00:12.000 --> 00:13.166
-Forward...
-Heather,

00:13.166 --> 00:14.583
You want to watch me
knock that bird’s nest

00:14.583 --> 00:15.750
out of the tree?

00:15.750 --> 00:18.000
No, I can’t do that today
because I’m helping Sam

00:18.000 --> 00:20.709
get ready for her audition
for the school play.

00:20.709 --> 00:23.709
TIM: Silence of the Lambs,
the Musical:

00:23.709 --> 00:25.166
A Starling is Born?

00:25.166 --> 00:27.375
-Yeah.
-Dad, you’re distracting us.

00:27.375 --> 00:30.208
No offense, Mom,
but you’re kind of taking up

00:30.208 --> 00:31.792
all the rehearsal time.

00:31.792 --> 00:33.083
Oh. Okay.

00:33.083 --> 00:35.959
I mean, I just think,
if you want the role of Clarice,

00:35.959 --> 00:38.000
you can’t just perform.

00:38.000 --> 00:40.208
You have to...

00:40.208 --> 00:43.000
perform.

00:43.000 --> 00:44.000
What’s she doing?

00:44.000 --> 00:46.250
What she’s been doing
for the last two hours.

00:46.250 --> 00:48.625
HEATHER: Five, six,
seven, eight.

00:48.625 --> 00:51.125
<i>♪ I know he’s eaten men ♪</i>

00:51.125 --> 00:53.291
<i>♪ I don’t know why he would ♪</i>

00:53.291 --> 00:55.750
<i>♪ To me, his biggest crime ♪</i>

00:55.750 --> 00:58.417
<i>♪ Was being misunderstood ♪</i>

00:58.417 --> 01:00.041
<i>♪ Silence of the lambs ♪</i>

01:00.041 --> 01:01.333
Baa! Shh.

01:01.333 --> 01:02.625
Baa! Shh.

01:02.625 --> 01:04.291
Fava!

01:04.291 --> 01:06.166
Mom, I’ve been working
on this for weeks.

01:06.166 --> 01:07.917
I’m just gonna focus
on my singing.

01:07.917 --> 01:10.333
Fine. Suit yourself,
but I wasn’t Annie

01:10.333 --> 01:12.709
because I focused on my singing.

01:12.709 --> 01:14.041
You were never Annie.

01:14.041 --> 01:15.125
Yeah. That’s what I said.

01:15.125 --> 01:16.959
I wasn’t Annie.

01:16.959 --> 01:18.166
♪

01:18.166 --> 01:19.291
Ooh! Ooh, ooh.

01:19.291 --> 01:21.875
Ooh, there’s our little star.

01:21.875 --> 01:23.208
Hey, how’d it go?

01:23.208 --> 01:25.333
Oh, you look sad,

01:25.333 --> 01:26.500
but you could be acting.

01:26.500 --> 01:28.542
-I’m the understudy.
-What?

01:28.542 --> 01:30.291
This girl,
who’s the worst singer ever,

01:30.291 --> 01:31.917
got the part of Clarice.

01:31.917 --> 01:34.417
I wish someone would make
a skin suit out of her.

01:34.417 --> 01:36.000
HEATHER: Hey, sweetie, sweetie,
no, no, no, no.

01:36.000 --> 01:39.291
Listen. Everything happens
for a reason.

01:39.291 --> 01:41.625
Okay, there is no reason
for this.

01:41.625 --> 01:42.875
♪

01:42.875 --> 01:44.000
Jack, hon,

01:44.000 --> 01:46.083
I need you
in your nude leotard

01:46.083 --> 01:49.458
for Buffalo Bill’s lotion dance.

01:49.458 --> 01:50.625
And, Carl?

01:50.625 --> 01:53.083
Carl, I know you’re strapped
to a hand truck,

01:53.083 --> 01:55.959
but your eyes
have to be dancing.

01:55.959 --> 01:57.500
Come on. Okay, and, everybody,

01:57.500 --> 01:59.792
general note, just pick it up.

01:59.792 --> 02:00.959
-Hi, Mr. Black, hi.
-Hi.

02:00.959 --> 02:02.625
HEATHER:
I’m--I’m Heather Hughes.

02:02.625 --> 02:03.959
I’m Sam’s mom,

02:03.959 --> 02:05.458
and I just wanted to come down
and talk to you--

02:05.458 --> 02:06.875
Oh, no, no, no,

02:06.875 --> 02:09.709
that basket is not
nearly big enough.

02:09.709 --> 02:13.000
It’s gotta fit all four
lotionettes and Precious.

02:13.000 --> 02:14.125
Where’s my Precious?

02:14.125 --> 02:15.583
Precious!

02:17.125 --> 02:19.166
Now, see, do you think
that he is gonna fit

02:19.166 --> 02:20.333
in that basket?

02:20.333 --> 02:21.834
Get real.

02:21.834 --> 02:22.750
Look, Mrs. Hughes,

02:22.750 --> 02:24.917
if this is about
the part of Clarice,

02:24.917 --> 02:26.208
I can’t discuss it.

02:26.208 --> 02:29.083
We at the school have
a strict "PNIS" policy.

02:29.083 --> 02:30.375
We’re very firm.

02:30.375 --> 02:31.709
You have a what?

02:31.709 --> 02:33.333
A "PNIS" policy.

02:33.333 --> 02:35.834
"Parental non-involvement
at school"?

02:35.834 --> 02:37.041
-Oh.
-All right, Clarice,

02:37.041 --> 02:38.750
let’s take it from the top
of the song.

02:38.750 --> 02:40.208
♪

02:40.208 --> 02:43.291
GEORGETTE:
<i>♪ I can’t even classify ♪</i>

02:43.291 --> 02:45.291
<i>♪ The clues I have ♪</i>

02:45.291 --> 02:47.250
<i>♪ To magnify ♪</i>

02:47.250 --> 02:51.917
<i>♪ When all I want to do</i>
<i>is cry ♪</i>

02:51.917 --> 02:53.709
Special Agent Starling.

02:53.709 --> 02:58.792
<i>♪ FBI ♪</i>

02:58.792 --> 03:01.542
MR. BLACK: Brava, Ms. Sloan.

03:01.542 --> 03:03.083
All right, back to one,
everybody.

03:03.083 --> 03:06.083
HEATHER: Wait, whoa,
she’s a Sloan?

03:06.083 --> 03:09.250
(dramatic piano music sting)

03:09.250 --> 03:10.917
MR. BLACK: No, Kiki!

03:10.917 --> 03:14.166
That music cue is way too early.

03:14.166 --> 03:15.333
(sighs)

03:15.333 --> 03:16.959
Can you play piano?

03:16.959 --> 03:19.250
HEATHER: Oh, this is outrageous.

03:19.250 --> 03:21.542
Sam is a much better singer
than this girl,

03:21.542 --> 03:24.083
but we didn’t donate a building
to the school.

03:24.083 --> 03:25.917
Donating a building?

03:25.917 --> 03:27.250
-That’s so ’80s.
HEATHER: Yeah.

03:27.250 --> 03:29.834
TIM: If we had
that kind of money,

03:29.834 --> 03:31.250
-I’d buy a submarine.
HEATHER: You know what?

03:31.250 --> 03:33.417
I don’t care how much money
the Sloans have.

03:33.417 --> 03:35.583
All right, that does not give
this teacher

03:35.583 --> 03:37.250
the right to play favorites.

03:37.250 --> 03:42.000
And when Mama sees injustice,
Mama fights injustice.

03:42.000 --> 03:43.625
Oh, please don’t
start singing.

03:43.625 --> 03:44.917
HEATHER: Five, six,
seven, eight.

03:44.917 --> 03:46.125
♪

03:46.125 --> 03:48.208
Sorry to make this
a legal matter,

03:48.208 --> 03:52.959
but my lawyer is here to assure
that this is taken seriously.

03:52.959 --> 03:54.208
Yeah, I’m not her lawyer.

03:54.208 --> 03:56.333
She just asked me
to go to lunch.

03:56.333 --> 03:58.250
Mrs. Hughes, like I said
on the phone,

03:58.250 --> 04:01.083
Mr. Black has final say
on all theater decisions.

04:01.083 --> 04:03.041
Okay, you know what,
let’s go down to the auditorium.

04:03.041 --> 04:05.667
Watch Georgette perform,
then watch Sam.

04:05.667 --> 04:07.000
Tell me what you think.

04:07.000 --> 04:11.166
All right,
let’s get this over with.

04:11.166 --> 04:14.709
So just not gonna have lunch
today, then.

04:14.709 --> 04:16.709
That’s cool.

04:16.709 --> 04:19.875
GEORGETTE:<i> ♪ In this hole</i>
<i>I’m just not me ♪</i>

04:19.875 --> 04:21.750
<i>♪ In this hole</i>
<i>I can never be ♪</i>

04:21.750 --> 04:22.875
HEATHER: Ugh.

04:22.875 --> 04:23.792
PRINCIPAL: Mr. Black,

04:23.792 --> 04:25.583
would you mind letting
Samantha perform?

04:25.583 --> 04:27.083
Oh, no. Not at all.

04:27.083 --> 04:29.625
Just like I don’t mind running
the Gay-Straight Alliance

04:29.625 --> 04:32.166
just because I’m
the theater teacher.

04:32.166 --> 04:34.458
Okay, uh, let’s take it
from the top

04:34.458 --> 04:36.041
of the lotion song.

04:36.041 --> 04:38.625
And, Samantha,
would you step in for us?

04:38.625 --> 04:39.792
Thanks.

04:39.792 --> 04:42.375
All right, and...

04:42.375 --> 04:44.333
Act now.

04:44.333 --> 04:46.542
♪

04:46.542 --> 04:49.750
SAMANTHA:<i> ♪ In this hole</i>
<i>I’m just not me ♪</i>

04:49.750 --> 04:52.959
<i>♪ In this hole I can never be ♪</i>

04:52.959 --> 04:56.250
<i>♪ In this hole</i>
<i>the world crashes down ♪</i>

04:56.250 --> 05:02.375
<i>♪ While it rubs the lotion</i>
<i>all around ♪</i>

05:02.375 --> 05:04.041
You didn’t cast her?

05:04.041 --> 05:07.792
SAMANTHA:<i> ♪ It puts the lotion</i>
<i>if you ask it ♪</i>

05:07.792 --> 05:09.875
<i>♪ It puts the lotion ♪</i>

05:09.875 --> 05:11.834
<i>♪ In the basket ♪</i>

05:11.834 --> 05:16.041
<i>♪ In the basket ♪</i>

05:16.041 --> 05:17.166
HEATHER: Oh, yes!

05:17.166 --> 05:19.125
That’s my daughter.

05:19.125 --> 05:20.792
-Let her finish.
-Okay.

05:23.834 --> 05:25.417
(bad Southern accent)
You see a lot,

05:25.417 --> 05:27.875
don’t you, Dr. Lecter?

05:27.875 --> 05:29.375
Why don’t you turn

05:29.375 --> 05:33.834
that high-powered perception
at yourself?

05:33.834 --> 05:36.375
Tell us what you see,

05:36.375 --> 05:41.709
or maybe you’re too afraid to.

05:41.709 --> 05:45.834
Legally speaking,
she is terrible.

05:45.834 --> 05:50.125
♪

05:50.125 --> 05:51.458
SINCLAIR: So I named
the character

05:51.458 --> 05:53.834
in this novel Oliver,
because that’s what he wants

05:53.834 --> 05:57.083
from his love interest:
all of her.

05:57.083 --> 05:58.250
Brilliant.

05:58.250 --> 05:59.291
Yes, I try to be so subtle

05:59.291 --> 06:01.291
that people barely
understand it.

06:01.291 --> 06:03.792
You really should
write this down

06:03.792 --> 06:06.125
so that people can learn
from your process.

06:06.125 --> 06:09.583
SINCLAIR: Oh, I’m, uh,
constantly recording myself.

06:09.583 --> 06:12.125
Pick up dry cat food.

06:12.125 --> 06:13.500
No, no.

06:13.500 --> 06:14.458
Wet.

06:14.458 --> 06:16.792
JOAN: Wet is so much
more expensive

06:16.792 --> 06:19.041
but so much better
for the animal.

06:19.041 --> 06:21.125
SINCLAIR: Isn’t it?
HEATHER: Hi. Hi.

06:21.125 --> 06:22.125
Sorry.

06:22.125 --> 06:23.709
JOAN: Wha--what are you
doing here?

06:23.709 --> 06:25.625
HEATHER: Oh, I just--I wanted
to see if you want to go

06:25.625 --> 06:26.792
and grab some lunch.

06:26.792 --> 06:28.375
Oh, is this your mother?

06:28.375 --> 06:29.333
Oh, stop.

06:29.333 --> 06:30.792
(laughter)

06:30.792 --> 06:31.834
HEATHER: Hi, I’m Heather.

06:31.834 --> 06:32.959
I’m Joan’s daughter.

06:32.959 --> 06:34.250
-Sinclair Wilde.
-Oh.

06:34.250 --> 06:37.500
Your mother
is an inspiration.

06:37.500 --> 06:40.417
It’s rare that I find
a student so...

06:40.417 --> 06:41.500
so stimulating.

06:41.500 --> 06:43.750
JOAN: Mm-hm.
We stimulate each other.

06:43.750 --> 06:45.417
-Yes.
-Oh. Wow.

06:45.417 --> 06:47.333
She has awakened
poetic urges

06:47.333 --> 06:51.041
I didn’t realize
I still...

06:51.041 --> 06:53.875
Make that diet cat food.

06:53.875 --> 06:55.792
He cares deeply
about animals.

06:55.792 --> 06:58.542
He’s a true renaissance man.

06:58.542 --> 07:01.959
SINCLAIR: Yeah.
Oh, and paper towels.

07:01.959 --> 07:03.834
♪

07:03.834 --> 07:05.583
HEATHER:
Matt, this is serious.

07:05.583 --> 07:07.917
-What?
-All right, listen.

07:07.917 --> 07:10.125
They were all over each other.

07:10.125 --> 07:13.041
Okay, but that doesn’t mean
that Mom is cheating on Dad.

07:13.041 --> 07:14.542
HEATHER:
Oh, have you not noticed

07:14.542 --> 07:15.959
that she talks
about that professor

07:15.959 --> 07:18.041
more than Greg talks
about being an inventor?

07:18.041 --> 07:19.333
You’re my big sister,
and I love you,

07:19.333 --> 07:20.583
but you have to stop jumping

07:20.583 --> 07:21.875
to these ridiculous conclusions.

07:21.875 --> 07:22.792
Like when you thought
the neighbor

07:22.792 --> 07:24.333
was running a brothel
out of his house.

07:24.333 --> 07:26.041
Oh, my--Matt, there were women

07:26.041 --> 07:27.667
parading in and out
of his house

07:27.667 --> 07:29.125
at all hours of the night.

07:29.125 --> 07:30.875
Those were his wife’s
hospice nurses.

07:30.875 --> 07:32.583
I don’t know, when those women
stopped coming around,

07:32.583 --> 07:34.542
he was pretty upset.

07:34.542 --> 07:35.875
Because his wife had just died.

07:35.875 --> 07:38.625
HEATHER: Oh, my God. Like
the hookers killed his wife.

07:38.625 --> 07:39.875
GREG: Hey, what you guys
talking about?

07:39.875 --> 07:42.000
-Nothing. It’s private.
-Oh, give it a rest, Matthew.

07:42.000 --> 07:44.625
You did not invent privacy,
all right?

07:44.625 --> 07:46.000
You’re not the inventor
in this family.

07:46.000 --> 07:47.709
Come on, you guys
always leave me out,

07:47.709 --> 07:48.667
ever since we were
little kids.

07:48.667 --> 07:50.250
We’re adults now, so tell me

07:50.250 --> 07:51.166
what you guys
are talking about

07:51.166 --> 07:53.834
or I’m gonna tell Mom.

07:53.834 --> 07:54.834
No.

07:54.834 --> 07:56.709
First you told me
that I was a bastard.

07:56.709 --> 07:57.917
Now you’re telling me that I am

07:57.917 --> 07:59.458
gonna come from a broken home?

07:59.458 --> 08:00.875
Don’t you think
it’s possible

08:00.875 --> 08:03.166
that Mom gets some
intellectual stimulation

08:03.166 --> 08:05.667
from this professor
that she doesn’t get from Dad?

08:05.667 --> 08:07.375
JOHN: Hey, guys,

08:07.375 --> 08:10.750
is this Cheeto’s hair
or your mom’s?

08:10.750 --> 08:11.959
This is Cheeto’s hairbrush.

08:11.959 --> 08:14.000
I know that for sure.

08:14.000 --> 08:15.792
HEATHER: I--I have no idea, Dad.

08:15.792 --> 08:17.000
Where is your mom?

08:21.709 --> 08:22.625
Yeah.

08:22.625 --> 08:23.875
♪

08:23.875 --> 08:24.875
Come on, you guys.
We gotta hurry up

08:24.875 --> 08:25.792
if we’re gonna follow Mom.

08:25.792 --> 08:27.000
Her class gets out
in half an hour.

08:27.000 --> 08:28.500
MATT: Shotgun.
GREG: No, I already called it.

08:28.500 --> 08:30.792
-In the house doesn’t count.
-No, I was in the hallway.

08:30.792 --> 08:32.875
HEATHER: Guys, we do not
have time for this.

08:32.875 --> 08:34.125
GREG: Well, then tell Matthew

08:34.125 --> 08:35.792
that you heard me call shotgun.

08:35.792 --> 08:37.458
All right, fine.
Matt, you drive.

08:37.458 --> 08:40.166
Shotgun! Ah!
New driver cleans the slate.

08:40.166 --> 08:41.375
Okay. Fine.

08:41.375 --> 08:42.667
I’ll sit
in the back for now.

08:42.667 --> 08:44.500
But you want to know what,
we are rotating seats

08:44.500 --> 08:46.500
every 20 minutes,
like on family road trips.

08:46.500 --> 08:47.458
HEATHER: Get in!

08:47.458 --> 08:49.792
(engine starts)

08:49.792 --> 08:52.792
GREG: Oh, man,
I just sat on a banana.

08:52.792 --> 08:54.583
♪

08:54.583 --> 08:56.458
HEATHER: All right,
her class just got out,

08:56.458 --> 08:57.875
so she should be...

08:57.875 --> 08:59.667
Oh, there she is.

08:59.667 --> 09:01.458
Okay, she’s on the move.

09:01.458 --> 09:03.333
All right, I’m ready.
Let’s do this.

09:03.333 --> 09:06.792
GREG: Four minutes left
until we switch seats, guys.

09:06.792 --> 09:13.625
♪

09:19.792 --> 09:22.250
HEATHER: Okay, guys,
she is at a motel.

09:22.250 --> 09:23.709
I--I don’t like
the look of this.

09:23.709 --> 09:26.083
GREG: Okay, Heather, a lot
of people go and visit motels.

09:26.083 --> 09:27.834
It doesn’t mean
anything bad is happening.

09:27.834 --> 09:30.000
I mean, look at that guy.

09:30.000 --> 09:31.750
-Selling drugs.
HEATHER: Yeah.

09:31.750 --> 09:33.291
Okay, right there.
She’s going into a room.

09:33.291 --> 09:35.000
I am sure that
the professor’s in there.

09:35.000 --> 09:36.792
He’s probably taking off
his tweed coat

09:36.792 --> 09:39.583
and getting ready
for an oral presentation.

09:39.583 --> 09:43.709
GREG: I’ll tell you right now,
I am not calling this guy Dad.

09:43.709 --> 09:45.000
Mom, open the door.

09:45.000 --> 09:48.417
I may be a bastard, but I am
not coming from a broken home.

09:50.417 --> 09:52.041
Kids,
what are you doing here?

09:52.041 --> 09:53.333
HEATHER: We are here
to keep you

09:53.333 --> 09:56.417
from making a terrible mistake.

09:56.417 --> 09:59.625
-Oh, oh...
-Joanie?

09:59.625 --> 10:01.834
Is this part
of the humiliation?

10:01.834 --> 10:04.667
I think we’re the ones
making a terrible mistake.

10:04.667 --> 10:07.542
I have to go.

10:07.542 --> 10:09.291
MATT: Couldn’t do this at home?
JOAN: No.

10:09.291 --> 10:13.125
Sylvia the housekeeper’s there
on Wednesdays,

10:13.125 --> 10:16.583
and your dad needs a headboard
for his move.

10:18.709 --> 10:20.166
GREG: Well, that’s great.

10:20.166 --> 10:21.750
Now, uh, every Wednesday

10:21.750 --> 10:23.792
I will just think of that.

10:23.792 --> 10:25.458
HEATHER: All right.
You know what? Yeah.

10:25.458 --> 10:28.333
I got carried away again,
and I am so sorry

10:28.333 --> 10:31.375
that we had to see
Dad tied up again.

10:31.375 --> 10:32.291
Well, at least this time

10:32.291 --> 10:34.208
he wasn’t dressed up
like Santa.

10:34.208 --> 10:36.625
♪

10:36.625 --> 10:38.709
Our electric bill
has doubled.

10:38.709 --> 10:40.500
Are you guys
running a space heater

10:40.500 --> 10:41.667
and a fan at the same time?

10:41.667 --> 10:43.875
Marriage
is about compromise.

10:46.166 --> 10:48.458
♪

10:48.458 --> 10:50.083
HEATHER: Okay.

10:50.083 --> 10:52.166
Because you’re not having sex,

10:52.166 --> 10:54.166
we thought that maybe
this would be a good time

10:54.166 --> 10:55.667
to talk to you.

10:55.667 --> 10:56.667
Your father and I think

10:56.667 --> 10:58.291
that you should
start paying rent.

10:58.291 --> 11:00.625
You want us to pay rent
to live in our own home?

11:00.625 --> 11:02.875
Take a look at
this cable bill, all right?

11:02.875 --> 11:05.291
We have a $150
pay-per-view charge

11:05.291 --> 11:06.917
for some Japanese anime series

11:06.917 --> 11:10.250
called Happy Raccoon
Sailor Princess.

11:10.250 --> 11:12.500
In our defense,
we thought it was a porn.

11:12.500 --> 11:14.875
You guys need to learn
about responsibility.

11:14.875 --> 11:16.583
This feels like
a macro-aggression.

11:16.583 --> 11:18.000
TIM: Well, I don’t know
what that is.

11:18.000 --> 11:20.208
Why are they
screaming at us?

11:20.208 --> 11:23.750
You need to pay rent
like real adults,

11:23.750 --> 11:26.000
unless you want
to go to college,

11:26.000 --> 11:29.208
in which case we will
completely support you.

11:29.208 --> 11:31.208
I have never felt
so unloved.

11:31.208 --> 11:32.917
And you know what?
If we’re gonna pay rent,

11:32.917 --> 11:34.333
we may as well live
in our own place,

11:34.333 --> 11:35.875
where Dad doesn’t have
to use our bathroom

11:35.875 --> 11:37.709
every time he has to soak.

11:37.709 --> 11:40.208
I didn’t ask to have corns,
God gave them to me.

11:40.208 --> 11:41.250
I know.

11:41.250 --> 11:42.291
♪

11:42.291 --> 11:44.667
Nice hat. Are you guys Southern?

11:44.667 --> 11:47.583
No, we’re just adults.

11:47.583 --> 11:50.041
MAN: Okay, uh,
so, your first place.

11:50.041 --> 11:51.750
Very exciting.
And let me just ask,

11:51.750 --> 11:52.834
how much can you afford in rent?

11:52.834 --> 11:54.875
Oh, well,
we haven’t compiled

11:54.875 --> 11:55.875
our financial dossier
quite yet,

11:55.875 --> 11:57.667
but we are, of course,
dollar cost averaging

11:57.667 --> 12:00.208
across the net gain,
so, uh, let’s just put that

12:00.208 --> 12:02.208
in the "We’ll get
back to you" column.

12:02.208 --> 12:04.000
Okay, guys. So, uh,
the way this works is:

12:04.000 --> 12:05.375
you’re gonna need
first month’s rent,

12:05.375 --> 12:07.083
last month’s rent,
and a security deposit.

12:07.083 --> 12:08.375
Wait, last month?

12:08.375 --> 12:10.291
We didn’t live in it
last month.

12:10.291 --> 12:11.583
Oh, dear.

12:11.583 --> 12:13.709
Don, let’s cut
to the chase.

12:13.709 --> 12:16.709
We can’t pay you today,
but we’re in a band

12:16.709 --> 12:18.375
and our music
is gonna be huge,

12:18.375 --> 12:20.625
and you can get in
on the ground floor.

12:20.625 --> 12:23.291
TYLER: Yeah. Think about that.

12:25.166 --> 12:26.417
Are you thinking?

12:26.417 --> 12:28.834
(chuckles)

12:30.375 --> 12:31.917
Here’s a place you can afford.

12:34.333 --> 12:36.166
This is just a drawing
of a duck.

12:36.166 --> 12:37.750
♪

12:37.750 --> 12:38.917
Yeah.

12:38.917 --> 12:40.375
♪

12:40.375 --> 12:41.291
TYLER:
And you’ve always helped me

12:41.291 --> 12:42.834
when no one else would, Pop-Pop.

12:42.834 --> 12:44.500
Look, you’re married now.

12:44.500 --> 12:45.709
It’s time to grow up.

12:45.709 --> 12:46.709
But it’s so hard.

12:46.709 --> 12:48.709
Everyone keeps telling us
no and stuff.

12:48.709 --> 12:50.333
And they keep
yelling at us.

12:50.333 --> 12:51.375
You millennials think

12:51.375 --> 12:53.125
everything’s gonna land
in your lap,

12:53.125 --> 12:56.875
but dreams don’t pay for houses,
money does.

12:56.875 --> 12:58.875
And sometimes sex.

12:58.875 --> 13:00.291
So we should have more sex?

13:00.291 --> 13:01.542
I don’t think I can
do that, Pop-Pop.

13:01.542 --> 13:03.250
JOHN: No, no, no, no.
Be resourceful.

13:03.250 --> 13:04.208
You kids are smart.

13:04.208 --> 13:06.000
Figure something out.

13:06.000 --> 13:07.583
You know what?
He’s right.

13:07.583 --> 13:09.291
We are really smart,

13:09.291 --> 13:10.917
and we just need
to work harder.

13:10.917 --> 13:12.375
CLEMENTINE:
Yeah, we can do that.

13:12.375 --> 13:14.125
You know, if there’s
one thing I know,

13:14.125 --> 13:16.166
it’s that the world is fair.

13:16.166 --> 13:17.208
There you go.

13:17.208 --> 13:18.208
Do things yourself.

13:18.208 --> 13:20.458
That’s the American way.

13:20.458 --> 13:22.375
Joanie! Will you make me
a sandwich?

13:22.375 --> 13:23.583
I’ll be in the hot tub.

13:23.583 --> 13:27.166
♪

13:27.166 --> 13:29.125
TYLER: Hey, big news!
HEATHER: What?

13:29.125 --> 13:31.125
TYLER: We found a place to live.
HEATHER: What?

13:31.125 --> 13:32.500
How did you do that?

13:32.500 --> 13:33.834
TYLER: Well, we went by
a bunch of colleges

13:33.834 --> 13:35.083
looking for opportunities.

13:35.083 --> 13:38.291
Oh, see, I told you
they’d figure it out.

13:38.291 --> 13:39.709
The best path, you guys.

13:39.709 --> 13:40.792
Was it ever.

13:40.792 --> 13:42.542
They had credit card
applications everywhere,

13:42.542 --> 13:43.834
so we got, like, ten of them,

13:43.834 --> 13:45.750
and we used the money
to buy a house.

13:45.750 --> 13:47.125
You what?

13:47.125 --> 13:49.041
You can’t buy a house
with credit cards.

13:49.041 --> 13:51.125
Then how’d we earn
so many airline points?

13:51.125 --> 13:52.333
TIM: Wait.

13:52.333 --> 13:54.208
How do you think you’re gonna
pay off all that debt?

13:54.208 --> 13:56.625
Well, you get cash back
on anything you buy,

13:56.625 --> 13:58.500
so we’ll be making money.

13:58.500 --> 14:00.208
I just hope we can
spend enough.

14:00.208 --> 14:03.041
Man, I miss being as dumb
as you guys.

14:03.041 --> 14:05.458
HEATHER:
So, where is this house?

14:05.458 --> 14:06.792
Come on, I’ll show you.

14:11.166 --> 14:12.792
What is that?

14:12.792 --> 14:14.125
CLEMENTINE: Isn’t it cute?

14:14.125 --> 14:16.166
HEATHER: Is that one of those
fancy little mailboxes?

14:16.166 --> 14:17.625
TYLER: No, it’s called
a "tiny house,"

14:17.625 --> 14:19.875
but normal-size people
can live in them, too.

14:19.875 --> 14:21.750
CLEMENTINE: Pop-Pop told us
to be resourceful,

14:21.750 --> 14:23.166
so we took his advice.

14:23.166 --> 14:26.041
Yep, so we are homeowners
now and real adults,

14:26.041 --> 14:27.709
and we don’t need to rely
on anyone for anything.

14:27.709 --> 14:29.375
CLEMENTINE: Mm.
TIM: Where you gonna put it?

14:29.375 --> 14:30.625
Well, we were
thinking backyard,

14:30.625 --> 14:32.750
but if you want to show it off,
we’re fine with front.

14:32.750 --> 14:33.750
CLEMENTINE:
Come on, honey.

14:33.750 --> 14:34.875
Let’s go home.

14:34.875 --> 14:37.583
♪

14:37.583 --> 14:41.291
Ugh, I really had hope
for that one.

14:41.291 --> 14:44.875
MALE SINGER:
<i>♪ Take my hand ♪</i>

14:44.875 --> 14:48.000
♪<i> This will be the golden age</i>
<i>for us ♪</i>

14:48.000 --> 14:49.000
♪

14:49.000 --> 14:50.417
Good God.

14:50.417 --> 14:53.625
MALE SINGER:
<i>♪ Uh-uh-uh-uh-oh ♪</i>

14:53.625 --> 14:55.041
TIM: Where are they going?

14:55.041 --> 14:57.333
MALE SINGER:
<i>♪ Take my hand ♪</i>

14:57.333 --> 15:00.166
<i>♪ Take my hand ♪</i>

15:00.166 --> 15:02.583
"Joan touches
Greg’s face."

15:02.583 --> 15:04.959
Are--are you sure you
can count on that?

15:04.959 --> 15:06.250
Bitch, please.

15:09.166 --> 15:13.542
♪

15:13.542 --> 15:15.250
GREG: Hey, Mom, will you
get me another plate?

15:15.250 --> 15:16.417
This one’s dirty.

15:16.417 --> 15:19.041
Oh, here, take mine.

15:19.041 --> 15:20.875
MATT: Oh!

15:20.875 --> 15:22.250
GREG: She got me!

15:22.250 --> 15:24.667
Mom got me!

15:24.667 --> 15:26.500
JOAN: Oh...

15:26.500 --> 15:27.834
COLLEEN: Um, what’s so special
about the rooster plate?

15:27.834 --> 15:29.041
No, oh, please don’t ask.

15:29.041 --> 15:31.542
HEATHER: Okay,
it’s the funniest story.

15:31.542 --> 15:34.000
All right, so I used to do
all of my holiday shopping

15:34.000 --> 15:35.500
from catalogs, and then...

15:35.500 --> 15:37.417
A catalog
is like a website,

15:37.417 --> 15:39.333
but it’s on paper.

15:39.333 --> 15:40.750
-Thank you.
-Okay, and so, um,

15:40.750 --> 15:42.709
one year, Heather wrote
the wrong item number

15:42.709 --> 15:44.500
-in her mail-in form, and...
-Oh.

15:44.500 --> 15:46.000
GREG: Oh, wait, wait,
let me tell his part.

15:46.000 --> 15:47.625
MATT: Oh, right, good, good.
GREG: So, instead of

15:47.625 --> 15:49.333
ordering slippers,

15:49.333 --> 15:52.208
she ordered Mom
this rooster plate.

15:52.208 --> 15:55.083
SAMANTHA: Now, Mom-Mom
sneaks the rooster plate

15:55.083 --> 15:56.792
in with the regular plates.

15:56.792 --> 15:58.792
GREG: And this time,
she got me!

15:58.792 --> 16:00.750
EVERYONE: Yay!

16:00.750 --> 16:02.625
COLLEEN: Yay.

16:02.625 --> 16:04.083
Am I missing something?

16:04.083 --> 16:05.625
Mostly their DNA.

16:05.625 --> 16:09.250
See, there seems to be something
in their genetic makeup

16:09.250 --> 16:12.583
that makes them think that story
is frickin’ hilarious,

16:12.583 --> 16:15.458
and, sadly,
I know everything

16:15.458 --> 16:17.375
that these people
will say or do

16:17.375 --> 16:19.250
for the next two hours.

16:19.250 --> 16:20.709
Like, how in two seconds,

16:20.709 --> 16:23.625
John’s gonna say a joke
and Heather’s not gonna like it?

16:23.625 --> 16:26.291
JOHN: It was kind of
embarrassing for you, hm?

16:26.291 --> 16:28.417
Just sitting there
with your cock out.

16:28.417 --> 16:30.750
HEATHER: Dad! Hi! Kids.

16:30.750 --> 16:33.041
JOHN: Well, a rooster
is also called a cock.

16:33.041 --> 16:34.750
Hey, I can say animals.

16:34.750 --> 16:38.458
♪

16:38.458 --> 16:40.083
Family Bingo.

16:40.083 --> 16:41.792
Oh, I am loving this idea.

16:41.792 --> 16:43.041
Okay, rules are:

16:43.041 --> 16:44.750
whatever a family member
might say or do,

16:44.750 --> 16:45.792
you put in a box.

16:45.792 --> 16:48.375
Then, first person
to fill their card wins.

16:48.375 --> 16:49.542
Like this?

16:49.542 --> 16:51.709
"John does something
super creepy with Cheeto."

16:51.709 --> 16:52.834
Yeah, that’s a solid start.

16:52.834 --> 16:54.458
-Right?
-Yeah, very good.

16:54.458 --> 16:55.583
You’re gonna be
so hard to beat.

16:55.583 --> 16:57.417
You have so much experience
with this family.

16:57.417 --> 16:59.500
Yeah, but I’m not blood,
okay?

16:59.500 --> 17:01.750
And I was all by myself
until you came along,

17:01.750 --> 17:04.792
so it’s very nice
to have an outsider buddy.

17:04.792 --> 17:08.083
Aw, that’s so sweet.

17:08.083 --> 17:10.917
"Colleen touches her heart
and says, ’Aw.’"

17:10.917 --> 17:13.000
One, nothing.

17:13.000 --> 17:14.375
HEATHER: Oh, hey, Mom?
-Yeah?

17:14.375 --> 17:16.291
HEATHER: Can you save some
of those potatoes for Tim?

17:16.291 --> 17:18.208
He’s always hungry
after surgery.

17:18.208 --> 17:20.792
"Heather mentions Tim
is a doctor." Boom.

17:20.792 --> 17:22.000
MATT: Oh, hey. There you are.

17:22.000 --> 17:23.250
You guys literally vanished.

17:23.250 --> 17:26.041
I was literally
about to call the cops.

17:26.041 --> 17:28.291
"Matt abuses the word
’literally.’"

17:28.291 --> 17:29.625
-This is almost too easy.
-I know.

17:29.625 --> 17:30.542
TIM: What’s too easy?

17:30.542 --> 17:31.667
Ooh, what are those pieces
of paper?

17:31.667 --> 17:33.166
-Nothing. Get out of here.
-Damn it.

17:33.166 --> 17:34.417
JOHN: Hey!

17:34.417 --> 17:37.750
What are you guys all doing
upside down, huh?

17:37.750 --> 17:40.250
(laughs)

17:40.250 --> 17:41.959
♪

17:41.959 --> 17:43.375
TIM: Family Bingo?

17:43.375 --> 17:44.458
This is awesome.

17:44.458 --> 17:46.083
COLLEEN:
Yeah, it’s a game changer.

17:46.083 --> 17:49.041
Suddenly, I want John to ask me
which type of Mexican I am.

17:49.041 --> 17:51.625
TIM: All right, I want to play.
JEN: Nah.

17:51.625 --> 17:52.542
COLLEEN:
Yeah, we should let him.

17:52.542 --> 17:54.083
He’s not real family, either.

17:54.083 --> 17:55.834
JEN: Oh, okay, fine, yeah.

17:55.834 --> 17:57.333
-But just don’t ruin it.
-Of course not!

17:57.333 --> 17:58.750
Look, since you guys
got a head start,

17:58.750 --> 18:00.083
what if I get
the four corners...

18:00.083 --> 18:01.458
JEN: No.
TIM: Okay, how about this?

18:01.458 --> 18:02.875
Instead of doing
the whole sheet,

18:02.875 --> 18:04.166
we just do, like, an "X."

18:04.166 --> 18:06.333
JEN: Nope.
TIM: I’m just spitballing here.

18:06.333 --> 18:07.709
But what if halfway through,
we switch our paper?

18:07.709 --> 18:09.417
JEN: All right,
"Tim ruins something."

18:09.417 --> 18:11.125
-Check.
-No, that doesn’t count.

18:11.125 --> 18:13.959
(shattering, clanking)

18:13.959 --> 18:16.083
But that does.

18:16.083 --> 18:17.333
I got to think
of something.

18:17.333 --> 18:18.333
JEN: Oh!

18:18.333 --> 18:21.583
"Tim saves the day."
You got that one?

18:21.583 --> 18:23.709
-No.
-No.

18:23.709 --> 18:25.709
Oh, I just ate peanut butter.

18:25.709 --> 18:27.333
Give the captain a kiss.

18:27.333 --> 18:28.709
TIM: Yes! That’s a two-for-one.

18:28.709 --> 18:30.583
"John refers to himself
as the captain.

18:30.583 --> 18:33.125
John tongue kisses the dog."

18:33.125 --> 18:34.291
Damn!

18:34.291 --> 18:36.583
Okay, time to play
a little offense.

18:36.583 --> 18:37.709
♪

18:37.709 --> 18:39.834
-Oh. Heather.
-Yeah?

18:39.834 --> 18:41.458
COLLEEN: I think it’s so great

18:41.458 --> 18:43.333
how you let Sam
play on her phone

18:43.333 --> 18:44.750
when she needs a break
from the family.

18:44.750 --> 18:46.083
HEATHER:
Hey, Samantha!

18:46.083 --> 18:48.583
Come on, you know no screens
at Sunday brunch.

18:48.583 --> 18:50.458
COLLEEN: Such a good mom.
HEATHER: Oh, thank you.

18:50.458 --> 18:51.834
COLLEEN: Yeah.

18:51.834 --> 18:53.500
♪

18:53.500 --> 18:54.500
-Hey, babe.
-Yeah?

18:54.500 --> 18:55.750
Try this, it’s so good.

18:58.917 --> 19:00.375
GREG: Yeah.

19:00.375 --> 19:01.583
-Ooh.
-What?

19:01.583 --> 19:03.583
JOAN: You’ve got something
on your...

19:03.583 --> 19:05.125
-There you go.
GREG: Thanks, Mom.

19:05.125 --> 19:06.667
TIM: I had that one, too,
but I wrote down,

19:06.667 --> 19:09.959
"Joan marks Greg
as her territory."

19:12.458 --> 19:13.625
♪

19:13.625 --> 19:15.375
COLLEEN: I just got
one box left. You?

19:15.375 --> 19:16.667
Yeah, me, too.
I just need Sophia

19:16.667 --> 19:18.250
to say a word
that Matt doesn’t know.

19:18.250 --> 19:19.208
I only got two left.

19:19.208 --> 19:21.291
Where’s my paper?
I just had it.

19:21.291 --> 19:22.834
JOAN: Guys, what’s this?

19:22.834 --> 19:26.208
"Matt mentions
high school glory days."

19:26.208 --> 19:28.000
You talking about my
three-touchdown game again, Mom?

19:28.000 --> 19:31.667
JOAN: "Heather thinks
we’re talking about her"?

19:31.667 --> 19:33.542
HEATHER: What’s that about me?
JOAN: What--what?

19:33.542 --> 19:34.667
Tim?

19:34.667 --> 19:37.417
-It’s a simple explanation...
-Mm-hm.

19:37.417 --> 19:38.542
-...that Jen will provide.
-Go ahead.

19:38.542 --> 19:40.166
What?

19:40.166 --> 19:42.583
They’re playing
People Bingo, Joan.

19:42.583 --> 19:44.458
Yeah, we used to play it
in ’Nam,

19:44.458 --> 19:47.417
only ours was more like
"if Bill loses a leg"

19:47.417 --> 19:49.208
or "Hank dies."

19:49.208 --> 19:51.041
It’s the same idea.

19:51.041 --> 19:55.291
You do it to survive
an intolerable situation.

19:55.291 --> 19:57.125
Is that what you think
about our brunch?

19:57.125 --> 19:58.041
JEN: No.
COLLEEN: No.

19:58.041 --> 19:59.625
No, it’s just--

19:59.625 --> 20:01.834
look at it
from our perspective, okay?

20:01.834 --> 20:03.667
Most of your stories
don’t include us,

20:03.667 --> 20:06.208
so when you start to reminisce,

20:06.208 --> 20:07.625
what are we supposed to do?

20:07.625 --> 20:10.583
COLLEEN: Well, Jen, we could
have a great attitude

20:10.583 --> 20:12.542
and put on our listening ears.

20:12.542 --> 20:14.458
TIM: "Colleen sucks up to Joan."

20:14.458 --> 20:16.875
Can I have that?
I only have one left.

20:16.875 --> 20:19.291
JEN: Look, we are
really so sorry

20:19.291 --> 20:21.542
that we had some fun
at your expense.

20:21.542 --> 20:23.333
No.

20:23.333 --> 20:25.542
We owe you an apology.

20:25.542 --> 20:27.834
You are so important to us.

20:27.834 --> 20:31.333
Your lives are woven into ours,

20:31.333 --> 20:33.375
and you make our lives golden.

20:33.375 --> 20:35.083
And I just hope
that when I’m gone,

20:35.083 --> 20:37.250
you continue to...

20:37.250 --> 20:39.500
to weave together.

20:39.500 --> 20:41.458
♪

20:41.458 --> 20:42.709
COLLEEN: Thank you.

20:42.709 --> 20:45.166
♪

20:45.166 --> 20:47.333
"Joan talks about
her own death."

20:47.333 --> 20:48.709
-Bingo!
-What?

20:48.709 --> 20:50.166
COLLEEN: Come on!

20:50.166 --> 20:52.000
Oh.

20:52.000 --> 20:53.208
Seriously?

20:53.208 --> 20:56.125
I mean...shucks.

20:56.125 --> 21:03.041
♪
